2.  NT77 ⇒ NT68 NT44, where

         covers tokens 6–9 (t78 t54 t46 t90), and  
      – The final NT25 ⇒ NT31 NT5 ⇒ 't14' 't14' covers tokens 10–11.

Thus S ⇒ NT3 NT77 ⇒ (t70 t63)(t63 t14 t14 t78 t54 t46 t90 t14 t14), exactly the given string. Yes

To see why S cannot generate this string, note that the only rule for S is

  S → NT3 NT77.

Thus the very first token must come from NT3.  NT3 has exactly two productions:

  NT3 → 't17'
  NT3 → NT17 NT6

Either way, whatever NT3 derives must begin with terminal t17 (if NT3 → 't17') or with whatever NT17 derives (if NT3 → NT17 NT6).  But NT17 → NT8 NT58, and NT8 only ever produces t35 or t69.  So any string from NT3 must start with t17, t35 or t69—but our input begins with t15.  Hence NT3 cannot cover the initial token t15, so S cannot derive the given 12‐token string.

 S → NT3 NT77.

NT3 has exactly two productions:

  NT3 → ’t17’

• If NT3 → ’t17’, it would produce the single token t17, but our input begins with t29, so that fails.

• If NT3 → NT17 NT6, then NT6 must produce its only terminal, t63 (NT6 → ’t63’). Thus any string derived by NT3 must end in t63, yet the input contains no t63 at any position. Hence NT3 cannot cover any nonempty prefix of the input.

Since NT3 can’t match the first part of the input, S can’t derive the 12‐token string.
